How to read the data

Pay attention to how your software is reading the data. The columns commodity_code and trade_value_usd must be read as character and numeric (i.e. not as integer) respectively. Ignoring this will introduce null values in the data after you read it.

The processed data comes in csv format and its compressed in gz. In R it can be used by using data.table without uncompressing it first, and you can also read it by using Python, Stata or almost any statistical software.

We invite you to read our documentation, but here is an R example function to read compressed data:

{{ partial "fread2.html" . }}

Note for Windows users: In order to read the data without uncompressing it first, you need to install zcat beforehand. Use the API

Raw data from UN Comtrade was updated on 2018-08-05

Processed datasets were updated on 2018-12-01

Using our API is straightforward. No limits, no speed restrictions. Just be nice.

To use the api you can access it by using your browser or a software such as RStudio.

Visit api.tradestatistics.io and type a valid query

Simple example

Visit api.tradestatistics.io/friend and api.tradestatistics.io/me

Adecuate example

Read the JSON data from the API and convert it to a table with R:

{{ partial "api_example.html" . }}
All the details about the API

You should probably start by inspecting api.tradestatistics.io/countries

The tables we provide at the moment are:

  • countries
  • products
  • reporters
  • rankings
  • yc (Year - Commodity)
  • yr (Year - Reporter)
  • yrc (Year - Reporter - Commodity)
  • yrp (Year - Reporter - Partner)
  • yrpc (Year - Reporter - Partner - Commodity)

countries returns the details associated to a country code such as country full name and continent.

products returns the details associated to a product code such as product full name and product group.

reporters by default returns the iso code of all reporting countries in 2016, use reporters?y=2010 or any value between 1962 and 2016 for a different year.

rankings works in the same way as reporters.

y* tables return information about countries and products, and they can be subsetted by year, reporter or partner. These tables requiere specific parameters such as yrpc?y=2016&r=chl&p=arg provided these queries have no default values.
